<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-132-992  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 132 992.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Jan 25 1990 v35 n2A pS26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Are you ready for the '90's? An EDN survey shows that many of youare not. (Engineering in the '90s)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Call, Barbara.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The results of an 'Engineering in the '90s' survey indicate thatboth engineers and their managers are not aware of industrychanges.andP;  Only 22 percent of the engineering managers and only 10percent of the engineers indicated that it was important toacquire manufacturing knowledge.andP;  More than half of the engineerssurveyed feel that manufacturing knowledge is somewhat or not atall important.andP;  Many of these same engineers are responsible formanufacturing, production, and productivity decisions.andP;  Answers todesign cycle questions varied widely.andP;  General and corporatemanagers estimated 15 months as the average design cycle time;manufacturing and production personnel said 21 months.andP;  Althoughtrends indicate the design cycle will shorten, 38 to 40 percent ofthe respondents think the cycle will lengthen.andP;  Pollsters fearthat engineers are approaching the '90s with a closed mind.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TrendsSurveyEngineeringAttitudeFuture of ComputingComputer-Aided EngineeringFuture Technologies.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   The importance of knowing design, costs, CAE tools and productcycles. (graph)Survey results indicating manufacturing trends. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>